\begin{abstract}
\noindent
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m_\ell)/(\sum \sqrt{m_\ell})^2 = 2/3$ for the charged leptons has held to one part in $10^5$ for over forty years without an accepted derivation. Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that this relation has a Descartes-circle interpretation: identifying lepton mass square roots with circle curvatures, the Koide relation is the precise condition under which the algebraically simple combination $\mathcal{F} \equiv (\sum \sqrt{m_\ell}) - \sqrt{\sum m_\ell}$ coincides with the outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. We compute this curvature for the observed lepton triple and report a numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV reproduces the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ within current lattice precision (residual $-0.019$~MeV against a total uncertainty of $\pm 0.814$~MeV). Under a Koide-conditioned null model with a log-uniform prior on triples, the observed match arises in $0.58\%$ of valid samples (95\% CI $[0.49\%,\,0.68\%]$); we report this as a model-conditional descriptive frequency under our chosen Monte Carlo construction, not as a p-value or hypothesis test. The hit fraction is robust to four alternative prior choices (range $0.26\%$--$0.58\%$, fold variation $2.2$). Of eight lepton-derived scale prescriptions tested, only $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ produces a hit; the next-best alternatives miss by $\pm 2\sigma$. We present this as a numerical observation, not a derivation or a prediction. We make no claim about an underlying mechanism. We disclose the order of operations leading to the observation and report scale, input, prior, and filter sensitivities along with the error budget decomposition.
\end{abstract}

%======================================================================
\section{Introduction}
%======================================================================

The Koide relation~\cite{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
holds for the observed charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$. Using the PDG~2024 values~\cite{PDG2024} ($m_e = 0.5109989$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6584$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.93 \pm 0.09$~MeV), one computes $Q = 0.666661$. Although the relation is not part of the standard Standard-Model curriculum, it has been the subject of continuous theoretical investigation since 1981, with derivation attempts, extensions to the neutrino and quark sectors, and geometric reinterpretations appearing across the intervening four decades; we cite the Rivero--Gsponer review~\cite{RiveroGsponer2005} as an entry point and~\cite{Foot1994,Sumino2009,RodejohannZhang2011,Rivero2011,Krolikowski2014} as representative further reading. We treat~(\ref{eq:koide}) as an empirical input.

In 2012, Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that the Koide relation has a Descartes-circle interpretation: identifying $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$, the lepton mass square roots are realizable as three of four curvatures of a mutually tangent Soddy circle configuration governed by the Descartes circle theorem. The Koide value $Q = 2/3$ is precisely the condition under which the algebraically simple combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ formed from the leptons coincides with the geometrically determined outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ of the configuration. We make this statement precise as Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} below. Kocik's own treatment uses a generalized intersecting-circle Descartes formula and explicitly sets the fourth curvature to zero (a degenerate ``line'' circle); he does not compute the non-trivial fourth curvature, and he does not connect any geometric quantity to a quark mass. Our contribution is that step.

We extend Kocik's construction by computing the outer Soddy curvature for the observed lepton triple, denoting it $\mathcal{F}$, and reporting a numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2$ equals the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. We make no theoretical claim. The contribution of this paper is the computation of $\mathcal{F}$ within Kocik's framework and the disclosure of the resulting numerical match, together with a Monte Carlo characterization of the observation's behavior under a family of Koide-conditioned toy null models, including sensitivity to alternative priors, scale prescriptions, and filter cutoffs.

%======================================================================
\section{The Koide relation as a Descartes condition}
%======================================================================

We summarize the Kocik construction~\cite{Kocik2012} for completeness and to fix notation.

The Descartes circle theorem~\cite{Coxeter1968} states that four mutually tangent circles in the plane, with curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3, k_4$, satisfy
\begin{equation}
(k_1 + k_2 + k_3 + k_4)^2 \;=\; 2\,(k_1^2 + k_2^2 + k_3^2 + k_4^2).
\label{eq:descartes}
\end{equation}
Given three curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3$, equation~(\ref{eq:descartes}) is a quadratic in $k_4$ with two real solutions
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,\pm} \;=\; (k_1 + k_2 + k_3) \;\pm\; 2\sqrt{k_1 k_2 + k_2 k_3 + k_1 k_3},
\label{eq:soddy}
\end{equation}
corresponding respectively to the inner and outer Soddy circles tangent to the original three. By convention, the larger-curvature solution $k_4^{\,+}$ corresponds to the smaller circle (the inner Soddy circle, nestled in the gap between the original three), and the smaller-curvature solution $k_4^{\,-}$ corresponds to the larger circle (the outer Soddy circle, conventionally drawn enclosing the original three). The relevant quantity for our purposes is the outer curvature $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$.

\begin{proposition}[Koide and the outer Soddy curvature, after Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012}]
\label{prop:koide_descartes}
Identify $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$. Let $e_1 = \sum_i \sqrt{m_i}$, $e_2 = \sum_{i<j} \sqrt{m_i m_j}$, and $p_2 = \sum_i m_i$. The outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration $(k_e, k_\mu, k_\tau)$ is
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,-} \;=\; e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}.
\label{eq:k4_geometric}
\end{equation}
The algebraically simpler expression
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;\equiv\; e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} \;=\; \big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big) - \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}
\label{eq:F_alg}
\end{equation}
coincides with $k_4^{\,-}$ if and only if the Koide relation $Q \equiv p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$ holds exactly.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The Soddy form follows from solving the quadratic~(\ref{eq:descartes}) for $k_4$ given $k_1, k_2, k_3$, using the identity $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$ to simplify the discriminant; the smaller-curvature root is $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. Setting $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ yields $4 e_2 = p_2$. Combined with $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$, this gives $e_1^2 = p_2 + p_2/2 = (3/2) p_2$, equivalently $p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$, which is the Koide condition. Conversely, if $Q = 2/3$ then $e_2 = e_1^2/6 = p_2/4$, so $2\sqrt{e_2} = \sqrt{p_2}$ and the two expressions agree. \qed
\end{proof}

Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} gives the precise content of Kocik's geometric reading of Koide. The Koide relation is the statement that the dimensionally simple combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$, formed without reference to circles, is in fact the outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration whose three input curvatures are the lepton mass square roots. The observed leptons satisfy $Q = 0.666661$, so the equality of~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}) and~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) holds to one part in $10^5$. In what follows we use the form~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) for numerical convenience and treat $\mathcal{F}$ as the (Koide-approximate) outer Soddy curvature; we quantify the residual difference numerically in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. Figure~\ref{fig:soddy} shows the geometric configuration schematically.

