Both null tests use a lower cutoff of $\mu_\star^{(i)} > 1$~GeV to ensure four-loop QCD running is reliable. To verify that this cutoff is not coupling the sample to the comparison observable, we re-run the tight null under three alternative cutoffs:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
$\mu_\text{min}$ & Tight-null hit fraction \\
\midrule
$0.7$~GeV (extrapolated; running not strictly trusted) & $0.50\%$ \\
$1.0$~GeV (baseline) & $0.58\%$ \\
$1.5$~GeV & $0.70\%$ \\
$2.0$~GeV (cuts above the lepton sum scale; trivially zero) & $0.00\%$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Across the three nontrivial cutoffs, the hit fraction varies by a factor of $1.4$, well below the factor-of-two threshold at which we would consider the filter to be doing significant work. The $2$~GeV cutoff is excluded because it cuts above the lepton-sum scale itself and trivially yields zero. We conclude that the result is stable under reasonable variations of the lower cutoff.

\subsection{Interpretation}

Before interpreting the numbers reported in this section, we state explicitly what they are and are not. The hit fractions are conditional frequencies under specific Monte Carlo constructions over an explicitly chosen family of toy null models. They are not p-values, do not constitute hypothesis tests against any physical null, and should not be interpreted as evidence against chance in any objective sense. We report them for reproducibility, and to characterize the observation's behavior within a family of toy nulls that bracket several plausible modeling choices; readers should weight any conclusion drawn from these numbers by the credibility they assign to the null family itself, which we make no claim is uniquely natural or exhaustive of all reasonable constructions.

With that framing in place: the tight-null Monte Carlo, conditioned on Koide-saturating triples and using our baseline prior, returns a hit fraction of $0.58\%$, which remains in the range $0.26\%$--$0.58\%$ across all four priors we tested. The loose null, which broadens the comparison to $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \in \{1, 2, 3\}$ against five quark species, returns $0.81\%$ on the same sample. The continuous scale-sensitivity scan shows a narrow $\pm 2.5\%$ window around $\mu_\star$ in which agreement with $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ holds, and the discrete scale-prescription test shows that no other lepton-derived scale prescription in the perturbative regime produces a hit. Both nulls are stable under variation of the prior and the filter cutoff at the levels reported in subsections~\ref{sec:prior_sensitivity} and~\ref{sec:filter}. These numbers describe the observation's behavior within the constructions we built; we draw no further inferential conclusion from them and make no significance claim.

%======================================================================
\section{Caveats and non-claims}
\label{sec:notclaims}
%======================================================================

We make the following non-claims explicit, because the intuitive reading of a numerical match between lepton-derived and quark-derived quantities tends to import claims we are not making.

\paragraph{Not a derivation.}
We have not derived $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework. The observation is post-hoc in the sense that all of $m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau$, and $m_s$ were known when the comparison was made.

\paragraph{Not a prediction.}
The relation was not written down in advance of the strange-quark measurement and then confirmed; the masses involved were already established. The Monte Carlo characterization reported in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} is independent of authorial chronology: it asks how often the relation arises within a Koide-conditioned toy null family, not whether it was anticipated.

\paragraph{Not a mechanism.}
We do not propose a flavor-symmetry mechanism, a modular construction, a flavon alignment, or a grand-unified embedding that would generate $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$. We do not claim relevance to any specific flavor model. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders without attempting to anticipate their answer.

\paragraph{Not the only algebraic route to a comparable number.}
Rivero~\cite{Rivero2011} showed independently in 2011 that the quark triple $(s, c, b)$ with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ satisfies a Koide-like relation $Q \approx 2/3$, and that chained Koide conditions (the ``Koide waterfall'') connect lepton and quark sectors algebraically; this construction recovers $m_s$ in the same numerical neighborhood as the Soddy curvature reported here. The two routes are conceptually distinct: Rivero's construction is purely algebraic and chains Koide conditions across triples, whereas the present construction is geometric and operates on a single Koide-saturating triple via the Descartes circle theorem. We view the convergence as supportive of both lines: it suggests that the lepton--strange numerical relation is structurally meaningful in more than one framing, rather than a coincidence specific to either approach.

\paragraph{Not a charm or bottom relation.}
We have examined the analogous question for $m_c$ and $m_b$ and find that no integer power of $\mathcal{F}$ matches either at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star$ within current lattice precision. The numerical proximity $\mathcal{F}^3 \approx m_c^{\msbar}(m_b)$ noted in earlier drafts of this work requires evaluating $m_c$ at the bottom-quark scale rather than at the natural lepton scale, and so requires a different scale prescription than the strange relation. We do not have a structural justification for that different prescription, and we therefore restrict the present note to the strange sector.

%======================================================================
\section{Discussion}
%======================================================================

The observation, if it is more than coincidence, suggests one of three possibilities. First, the Koide relation may have a geometric origin that has not been recognized, and the Soddy connection may be its geometric content; in that case the present observation extends the same geometric structure into the strange sector via the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. Second, the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ may be the natural matching scale of some flavor mechanism that produces $m_s$ from leptonic input, in which case the observation is a constraint that any such mechanism must satisfy. Third, the observation may be a coincidence of the kind that Koide's relation itself might be: an unexplained numerical regularity that nonetheless has remained stable as measurements have improved, and that any future explanation of Koide will eventually need to account for. We do not argue for any of the three. We report the observation for the record without claiming inferential force beyond what the model-conditional frequencies in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} support.

%======================================================================
\section*{Computational note}
%======================================================================

All numerical results in this paper are reproducible with the open-source Python code at~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}. Four-loop $\msbar$ running is performed via CRunDec~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.273$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = 4.183$~GeV. Lepton inputs are PDG~2024 charged-lepton pole masses. Quark inputs are FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ averages for light quarks and PDG~2024 for heavy quarks. The null-model sampler uses a fixed random seed for reproducibility; sample size is $10^5$ candidate triples for both tight and loose null tests, replicated across four priors and four filter cutoffs. Total runtime for the full robustness analysis is under five minutes on a laptop.

